Encoding type for HTML page while saving the file is UTF-8. Extension can be .htm or .html
-------------------------
A simple HTML document:
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
<title>Page Title</title>
</head>
<body>

<h1>My First Heading</h1>
<p>My first paragraph.</p>

</body>
</html>

The <!DOCTYPE> declaration is not an HTML tag; it is an instruction to the web browser about what version of HTML the page is written in. 
The <html> element is the root element of an HTML page
The <head> element contains meta information about the document. 
The <title> element specifies a title for the document
The <body> element contains the visible page content
-------------------------------
element:
An element in HTML represents some kind of structure or semantics and generally consists of a start tag, content, and an end tag. 
The following is a paragraph element:
<p>
This is the content of the paragraph element.
</p>
HTML tags are not case sensitive: <P> means the same as <p>.
-----------------------------
<head> element:
The most common elements found in the <head> tag are: <title>, <meta>, <link> and <script> tags.
-------------------------------
<meta> element:
The HTML <meta> tag contains information or metadata that is not directly visible on the web page, but is used by browsers and 
search engines.

<!doctype html>
<html>
<head>
<meta charset="UTF-8">
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
<meta name="description" content="The HTML meta tag is an element that resides within the HTML head tag.">
<meta name="keywords" content="html, meta, tag, element">
<meta name="author" content="www.techonthenet.com">
<title>HTML 5 Example by www.techonthenet.com</title>
</head>
<body>
</body>
</html>
In this HTML 5 Document example, we have created 5 meta tags. The first meta tag (charset) defines the character 
encoding for the HTML document. The second meta tag (viewport) is used when designing a responsive web site.
A <meta> viewport element gives the browser instructions on how to control the page's dimensions and scaling.
The width=device-width part sets the width of the page to follow the screen-width of the device 
(which will vary depending on the device).
The initial-scale=1.0 part sets the initial zoom level when the page is first loaded by the browser.
The third meta tag (description) provides a description for the web page for the search engines.
The fourth meta tag (keywords) provides keywords for the search engines. 
The final meta tag (author) defines the author of the web page.
------------------------------------------
<link> element:
The <link> tag defines a link between a document and an external resource.
The <link> tag is used to link to external style sheets.
for example,
<head>
  <link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="theme.css">
</head>
-----------------------------------------
<script> element:
The HTML <script> tag is used to embed or reference a client-side script such as JavaScript. 
There are two ways that you can use the <script> tag. You can either embed the code within the <script> tags or 
you can reference a file that includes the code.

Embedded Code:
<script type="text/javascript">
  client-side scripting goes here ...
</script>

Reference a File:
<script src="/js/functions.js" type="text/javascript"></script>
---------------------------------------------
HTML Headings:
HTML headings are defined with the <h1> to <h6> tags.
<h1> is the biggest and <h6> is the smallest.
for example,
<h1>This is heading 1</h1>
<h2>This is heading 2</h2>
-------------------------------------
<p> element:
HTML paragraphs are defined with the <p> tag.'enter' in the paragraph will be considered as single space in the browser.
<p>This is a paragraph.</p>
-----------------------------------
<a> element:
HTML links are defined with the <a> tag.
<a href="https://www.w3schools.com">This is a link</a>
---------------------------------
<img> element:
HTML images are defined with the <img> tag.
<img src="w3schools.jpg" alt="W3Schools.com" width="104" height="142">
---------------------------------
HTML Attributes:
All HTML elements can have attributes
Attributes provide additional information about an element
Attributes are always specified in the start tag
Attributes usually come in name/value pairs like: name="value"
for example,
<a href="https://www.w3schools.com">This is a link</a>. Here href is an attribute.
<p style="color:red">I am a paragraph</p>. Here style is an attribute.
<p title='John "ShotGun" Nelson'>. Here title is an attribute.
--------------------------------
<hr> element:
Displays an horizontal rule. For example,
<h1>This is heading 1</h1>
<p>This is some text.</p>
<hr>
<h2>This is heading 2</h2>
<p>This is some other text.</p>
<hr>
---------------------------------
<br> element:
<br> element defines a line break.
---------------------------------
<pre> Element:
<pre> element defines preformatted text. i.e., the paragraph will be printed as it is with 'spaces' and 'enters'.
For example,
<pre>
  My Bonnie lies over the ocean.

  My Bonnie lies over the sea.

  My Bonnie lies over the ocean.

  Oh, bring back my Bonnie to me.
</pre>
----------------------------------------
The HTML Style Attribute:
Setting the style of an HTML element, can be done with the style attribute.
It has the following syntax:
<tagname style="property:value;">
The property is a CSS property. The value is a CSS value.

For example1,
<body style="background-color:powderblue;">
<h1>This is a heading</h1>
<p>This is a paragraph.</p>
</body>
For example2,
<h1 style="color:blue;">This is a heading</h1>
<p style="color:red;">This is a paragraph.</p>
For example3,
<h1 style="font-family:verdana;">This is a heading</h1>
<p style="font-family:courier;">This is a paragraph.</p>
For example4,
<h1 style="font-size:300%;">This is a heading</h1>
<p style="font-size:160%;">This is a paragraph.</p>
For example5,
<h1 style="text-align:center;">Centered Heading</h1>
<p style="text-align:center;">Centered paragraph.</p>
----------------------------------------------------
<b> element:
defines bold text, without any extra importance.
<b>This text is bold</b>
--------------------------------------
<strong> element:
defines strong text, with added semantic "strong" importance.
"Strong" could (and often does) mean "bold" in a browser,but it could also mean a lower tone for a
speaking program like Jaws (for blind people) or be represented by an underline (since you can't bold a bold) on a Palm Pilot.
<strong>This text is strong</strong>
---------------------------------------
<i> element:
defines italic text, without any extra importance.
<i>This text is italic</i>
-----------------------------------
<em> element:
defines emphasized text, with added semantic importance.
<em>This text is emphasized</em>

Browsers display <strong> as <b>, and <em> as <i>. However, there is a difference in the meaning of these tags: 
<b> and <i> defines bold and italic text, but <strong> and <em> means that the text is "important".
----------------------------------
<small> element:
defines smaller text.
<h2>HTML <small>Small</small> Formatting</h2>
------------------------------------
<mark> element:
defines marked or highlighted text.
<h2>HTML <mark>Marked</mark> Formatting</h2>
-------------------------------------
<del> element:
defines deleted (removed) text with a scratch mark on it.
<p>My favorite color is <del>blue</del> red.</p>
-------------------------------------
<ins> element:
defines inserted (added) text with an underline.
<p>My favorite <ins>color</ins> is red.</p>
------------------------------------------
<sub> element:
defines subscripted text.
<p>This is <sub>subscripted</sub> text.</p>
---------------------------------------
<sup> element:
defines superscripted text.
<p>This is <sup>superscripted</sup> text.</p>
-------------------------------------
<q> element:
defines a short quotation.Browsers usually insert quotation marks around the <q> element.
<p>WWF's goal is to: <q>Build a future where people live in harmony with nature.</q></p>
--------------------------------------
<blockquote> element:
Browsers usually indent <blockquote> elements. i.e., it displays paragraph with neatly arranged.
<blockquote>
For 50 years, WWF has been protecting the future of nature.
The world's leading conservation organization,
WWF works in 100 countries and is supported by
1.2 million members in the United States and
close to 5 million globally.
</blockquote>
-------------------------------------
<abbr> element:
defines an abbreviation or an acronym.
<p>The <abbr title="World Health Organization">WHO</abbr> was founded in 1948.</p>
-------------------------------------
 <address> element:
 defines contact information (author/owner) of a document or an article.The <address> element is usually displayed in italic.
<address>
Written by John Doe.<br> 
Visit us at:<br>
Example.com<br>
Box 564, Disneyland<br>
USA
</address>
--------------------------------------
<cite> element:
defines the title of a work.Browsers usually display <cite> elements in italic.
<p><cite>The Scream</cite> by Edvard Munch. Painted in 1893.</p>
-------------------------------------
<bdo> element:
defines bi-directional override.The <bdo> element is used to override the current text direction.It shows an 'ulta' line.
<bdo dir="rtl">This text will be written from right to left</bdo>
--------------------------------------
HTML Comment:
Used for commenting in between the code.Comments are not displayed by the browser, but they can help document your HTML source code. 
<!-- Write your comments here -->
